# Bash Special Symbols Cheat Sheet

## Positional & Special Parameters

| Symbol | Meaning | Example |
|--------|----------|----------|
| `$0` | Script name | `echo "$0"` |
| `$1 $2 ...` | 1st, 2nd argument | `echo "$1"` |
| `$#` | Number of arguments | `echo "$#"` |
| `$@` | All arguments (separate) | `"$@"` |
| `$*` | All arguments (single string) | `"$*"` |
| `$$` | Current process ID | `echo "$$"` |
| `$!` | Last background PID | `sleep 10 & echo $!` |
| `$?` | Exit status of last command | `echo "$?"` |
| `$_` | Last argument of previous command | Useful in scripts |

---

## Variable Expansion (`$` family)

### Basic
$name
${name}

Use {} to avoid ambiguity:

echo "${file}_backup"
Default / Fallback Values
Syntax	Meaning
${var:-value}	Use default if unset or empty
${var:=value}	Set default if unset
${var:+value}	Use value if var exists
${var:?error}	Exit with error if unset

Example:
echo "${USER:-guest}"
String Operations
Syntax	Meaning
${#var}	Length
${var:3}	Substring
${var:3:2}	Substring with length
${var#pattern}	Remove shortest prefix
${var##pattern}	Remove longest prefix
${var%pattern}	Remove shortest suffix
${var%%pattern}	Remove longest suffix
Array Symbols
Syntax	Meaning
${arr[0]}	First element
${arr[@]}	All elements separately
${arr[*]}	All elements as one string
${#arr[@]}	Number of elements
Command & Arithmetic
Command Substitution
$(command)

Example:
today=$(date)

Old style (avoid):

`date`
Arithmetic Expansion
$((expression))

Example:
echo $((5 + 3))
Quoting Symbols
Symbol	Meaning
" "	Allow variable expansion
' '	Literal text (no expansion)
\	Escape next character

Example:
echo "$HOME"   # expands
echo '$HOME'   # prints literally
Redirection & Pipes
Symbol	Meaning
>	Redirect output (overwrite)
>>	Append output
<	Redirect input
`	`
2>	Redirect errors
&>	Redirect stdout + stderr
Background & Control
Symbol	Meaning
&	Run in background
;	Command separator
&&	Run next if success
`	

Example:
make && echo "Build OK"
Wildcards (Globbing)
Symbol	Meaning
*	Any characters
?	Single character
[abc]	One of listed
[a-z]	Range

Example:
ls *.txt
Test / Condition Symbols

Used in [[ ... ]] or [ ... ]

Symbol	Meaning
-f	File exists
-d	Directory exists
-z	String empty
-n	String not empty
==	String equals
!=	Not equal
-eq -ne -lt -gt	Numeric comparisons

